	@{"     " Link "NODE_ENVVAR_HIRESCRSR"} HIRESCRSR
	@{"     " Link "NODE_ENVVAR_KEEPAMIGAVIDEO"} KEEPAMIGAVIDEO
	@{"     " Link "NODE_ENVVAR_NOPASSTHROUGH"} NOPASSTHROUGH
	@{"     " Link "NODE_ENVVAR_PLANES2FAST"} PLANES2FAST
	@{"     " Link "NODE_ENVVAR_SAVEMEM"} SAVEMEM
	@{"     " Link "NODE_ENVVAR_SUPERGELS"} SUPERGELS
	@{"     " Link "NODE_ENVVAR_SUPERLAYERS"} SUPERLAYERS
	@{"     " Link "NODE_ENVVAR_USESEMAPHORES"} USESEMAPHORES
	@{"     " Link "NODE_ENVVAR_WBPATSPEEDUP"} WBPATSPEEDUP

@EndNode

@Node "NODE_ENVVAR_ALERTEMU" "CyberGraphX4.guide/NODE_ENVVAR_ALERTEMU"
@Prev "NODE_ENVVAR"
@Next "NODE_ENVVAR_CPUP2C"
@Toc "NODE_ENVVAR"
@{Code}

	@{u}cybergraphx/ALERTEMU@{uu}

		By setting this variable, DisplayAlert(), (The Screens you get when
	the machine crashes.) will be placed on an cybergraphx screen.

	By setting this variable, you can switch off 15bit modes to reduce "
	screenmode list length. The Modes are still available but hidden.
	This can be done by:

        	setenv cybergraphx/ALERTEMU="1"

	This value is only read one at startup time, it can't be changed
	"online".

@EndNode

@Node "NODE_ENVVAR_CPUP2C" "CyberGraphX4.guide/NODE_ENVVAR_CPUP2C"
@Prev "NODE_ENVVAR_ALERTEMU"
@Next "NODE_ENVVAR_HIDE15BIT"
@Toc "NODE_ENVVAR"
@{Code}

	@{u}cybergraphx/CPUP2C@{uu}

		By setting this variable, the planar-to-chunky conversion
	will be done by the CPU (in contrast to the blitter-conversion)
	Therefore the ugly-looking "planar" blitting-effects are gone,
	but the software-conversion is slower.
	The cpu-conversion can be activated by:

        	setenv cybergraphx/CPUP2C="1"

	(this creates the file env:cybergraphx/CPUP2C
	-> you have to copy this file to envarc:cybergraphx/ if
	you want the variable permanently to be set)

@EndNode


@Node "NODE_ENVVAR_HIDE15BIT" "CyberGraphX4.guide/NODE_ENVVAR_HIDE15BIT"
@Prev "NODE_ENVVAR_CPUP2C"
@Next "NODE_ENVVAR_HIRESCRSR"
@Toc "NODE_ENVVAR"
@{Code}

	@{u}cybergraphx/HIDE15BIT@{uu}

		By setting this variable, you can switch off 15bit modes to reduce
	screenmode list length. The Modes are still available but hidden.
	This can be done by:

		setenv cybergraphx/HIDE15BIT="1"

	This value is only read one at startup time, it can't be changed
	"online".

@EndNode



@Node "NODE_ENVVAR_HIRESCRSR" "CyberGraphX4.guide/NODE_ENVVAR_HIRESCRSR"
@Prev "NODE_ENVVAR_HIDE15BIT"
@Next "NODE_ENVVAR_KEEPAMIGAVIDEO"
@Toc "NODE_ENVVAR"
@{Code}

	@{u}cybergraphx/HIRESCRSR@{uu}

		By setting this variable, the Lores-Sprites on non-AA-machines
	become Hires-sprites (they are no longer doubled by
	the CyberGraphX software).
	This variable is identical to the tooltype HIRESSPRITE of older 
	Picasso-monitor files Hiressprites can be activated by:

        	setenv cybergraphx/HIRESCRSR="1"

	(this creates the file env:cybergraphx/HIRESCRSR
	 -> you have to copy this file to envarc:cybergraphx/ if
	you want the variable permanently to be set)

@EndNode


@Node "NODE_ENVVAR_KEEPAMIGAVIDEO" "CyberGraphX4.guide/NODE_ENVVAR_KEEPAMIGAVIDEO"
@Prev "NODE_ENVVAR_HIRESCRSR"
@Next "NODE_ENVVAR_NOPASSTHROUGH"
@Toc "NODE_ENVVAR"
@{Code}

	@{u}cybergraphx/KEEPAMIGAVIDEO@{uu}

		If this option is disabled, everytime a CyberGraphX display
	becomes frontscreen, Amiga display DMA is switched off in order
	to increase chipmem access speed. You can avoid this by enabling
	this option.

        	setenv cybergraphx/KEEPAMIGAVIDEO="1"

	This value is only read one at startup time, it can't be changed
	"online".

@EndNode


@Node "NODE_ENVVAR_NOPASSTHROUGH" "CyberGraphX4.guide/NODE_ENVVAR_NOPASSTHROUGH"
@Prev "NODE_ENVVAR_KEEPAMIGAVIDEO"
@Next "NODE_ENVVAR_PLANES2FAST"
@Toc "NODE_ENVVAR"
@{Code}

	@{u}cybergraphx/NOPASSTHROUGH@{uu}

		THIS IS A MASTER SWITCH. If this option is enabled, the monitor switch on every
	CyberGraphX supported board is deactivated. This option is required for multi
	monitor systems. It is disabled by default.
	If NOPASSTHROUGH=0 (No) then the tooltype PASSTHROUGH can be used. 
	If NOPASSTHROUGH=1 (Yes) then the tooltype PASSTHROUGH is not used!

        	setenv cybergraphx/NOPASSTHROUGH="1"

	This value can be changed online.

@EndNode


@Node "NODE_ENVVAR_PLANES2FAST" "CyberGraphX4.guide/NODE_ENVVAR_PLANES2FAST"
@Prev "NODE_ENVVAR_NOPASSTHROUGH"
@Next "NODE_ENVVAR_SAVEMEM"
@Toc "NODE_ENVVAR"
@{Code}

	@{u}cybergraphx/PLANES2FAST@{uu}

		With this option on, non displayable planar bitmaps are allocated
	in fast memory. This options speeds up handling of planar bitmaps
	but could lead to problems with amiga graphics which insist on
	planar graphics placed in chip memory. Take care when using this
	option.

        	setenv cybergraphx/PLANES2FAST="1"

	This value is only read one at startup time, it can't be changed
	"online".

@EndNode



@Node "NODE_ENVVAR_SAVEMEM" "CyberGraphX4.guide/NODE_ENVVAR_SAVEMEM"
@Prev "NODE_ENVVAR_PLANES2FAST"
@Next "NODE_ENVVAR_SUPERGELS"
@Toc "NODE_ENVVAR"
@{Code}

	@{u}cybergraphx/SAVEMEM@{uu}

		CyberGraphX will reduce memory consumption in less or equal 16
	colour modes, CyberGraphX keeps a planar representation of the screen
	bitmap in fast memory and a chunky representation in video memory.

		setenv cybergraphx/SAVEMEM="1"

	This value is only read one at startup time, it can't be changed
	"online".

@EndNode

@Node "NODE_ENVVAR_SUPERGELS" "CyberGraphX4.guide/NODE_ENVVAR_SUPERGELS"
@Prev "NODE_ENVVAR_SAVEMEM"
@Next "NODE_ENVVAR_SUPERLAYERS"
@Toc "NODE_ENVVAR"
@{Code}

	@{u}cybergraphx/SUPERGELS@{uu}

		This env can activate a replacement for the original CyberGraphX GELs system.
	GELs = Graphic ELementS, this includes things like blitter objects and effects
	the speed of things like moving icons or opus drag and drop stuff. It will also
	give you superimposed dragging in hi/truecolor! It is disabled by default (=0).
	
        	setenv cybergraphx/SUPERGELS="1"

	This value is only read one at startup time, it can't be changed
	"online".
@EndNode


@Node "NODE_ENVVAR_SUPERLAYERS" "CyberGraphX4.guide/NODE_ENVVAR_SUPERLAYERS"
@Prev "NODE_ENVVAR_SUPERGELS"
@Next "NODE_ENVVAR_USESEMAPHORES"
@Toc "NODE_ENVVAR"
@{Code}

	@{u}cybergraphx/SUPERLAYERS@{uu}

		This env can activate a new, fast layers replacement. Will speed layers up a lot,
	especially when using many windows.

        	setenv cybergraphx/SUPERLAYERS="1"

	This value is only read one at startup time, it can't be changed
	"online".

@EndNode


@Node "NODE_ENVVAR_USESEMAPHORES" "CyberGraphX4.guide/NODE_ENVVAR_USESEMAPHORES"
@Prev "NODE_ENVVAR_SUPERLAYERS"
@Next "NODE_ENVVAR_WBPATSPEEDUP"
@{Code}

	@{u}cybergraphx/USESEMAPHORES@{uu}

		Enabling of this env activates use of semaphores to avoid disabling of
	multitasking under certain conditions. Enabling this option might
	lead to lockups under certain conditions but overall is more system
	friendly.

		setenv cybergraphX/USERSEMAPHORES="1"

	This value is only read one at startup time, it can't be changed
	"online".

@EndNode


@Node "NODE_ENVVAR_WBPATSPEEDUP" "CyberGraphX4.guide/NODE_ENVVAR_WBPATSPEEDUP"
@Prev "NODE_ENVVAR_USESEMAPHORES"
@Next "NODE_TTYPES"
@Toc "NODE_ENVVAR"
@{Code}

	@{u}cybergraphx/WBPATSPEEDUP@{uu}

		Enabling this variable activates a patch that should speed standard wb 
	pattern backfills. Since it could interfere with some
	hacks widely spread, it is disabled by default. It can be enabled by
	setting env:cybergraphx/WBPATSPEEDUP to 1.

		setenv cybergraphX/WBPATSPEEDUP="1"

	This value is only read one at startup time, it can't be changed
	"online".

@EndNode



@Node "NODE_TTYPES" "CyberGraphX4.guide/NODE_TTYPES"
@Prev "Main"
@Next "NODE_TTYPES_ADVANCEDCLK"
@Toc "Main"
@{CODE}

	@{fg highlight}@{b}Driver Tooltypes@{ub}@{fg text}


	The following driver tooltypes are supported by @{i}CyberGraphX4 @{ui} drivers:


	@{"     " Link "NODE_TTYPES_ADVANCEDCLK"} ADVANCEDCLK
	@{"     " Link "NODE_TTYPES_BITMAPCACHE_"} BITMAPCACHE
	@{"     " Link "NODE_TTYPES_BLACKBORDER"} BLACKBORDER
	@{"     " Link "NODE_TTYPES_BOOTLOGO"} BOOTLOGO
	@{"     " Link "NODE_TTYPES_DRAGGING"} DRAGGING
	@{"     " Link "NODE_TTYPES_MULTIMEDIAMEM"} MULTIMEDIAMEM
	@{"     " Link "NODE_TTYPES_PACKED24"} PACKED24
	@{"     " Link "NODE_TTYPES_PASSTHROUGH"} PASSTHROUGH
	@{"     " Link "NODE_TTYPES_SCROLLMASK"} SCROLLMASK
	@{"     " Link "NODE_TTYPES_USEROXXLER"} USEROXXLER

@EndNode

@Node "NODE_TTYPES_ADVANCEDCLK" "CyberGraphX4.guide/NODE_TTYPES_ADVANCEDCLK"
@Prev "NODE_TTYPES"
@Next "NODE_TTYPES_BITMAPCACHE"
@Toc "NODE_TTYPES"
@{CODE}

	@{u}Tooltype ADVANCEDCLK (CV64 and CV64/3D only)@{uu}

	Allows 'overclocking' of the CV64/CV3D cards, when used with CGXModeV4
	Default is 'ADVANCEDCLK=No'.

@EndNode


@Node "NODE_TTYPES_BITMAPCACHE" "CyberGraphX4.guide/NODE_TTYPES_BITMAPCACHE"
@Prev "NODE_TTYPES_ADVANCEDCLK"
@Next "NODE_TTYPES_BLACKBORDER"
@Toc "NODE_TTYPES"
@{CODE}

	@{u}Tooltype BITMAPCACHE@{uu}

		Setting 'BITMAPCACHE=YES' will cause Caching of bitmaps that allows faster
	window sizing/moving for smart refresh windows.

@EndNode


@Node "NODE_TTYPES_BLACKBORDER" "CyberGraphX4.guide/NODE_TTYPES_BLACKBORDER"
@Prev "NODE_TTYPES_BITMAPCACHE"
@Next "NODE_TTYPES_BOOTLOGO"
@Toc "NODE_TTYPES"
@{CODE}

	@{u}Tooltype BLACKBORDER (RetinaZ3 only)@{uu}

		By setting 'BLACKBORDER=YES' will cause the border around the screen
	to be black. The Retina BLT Z3 always uses color0 by default where other cards
	always use black. Default is 'BLACKBORDER=NO'.

@EndNode


@Node "NODE_TTYPES_BOOTLOGO" "CyberGraphX4.guide/NODE_TTYPES_BOOTLOGO"
@Prev "NODE_TTYPES_BLACKBORDER"
@Next "NODE_TTYPES_DRAGGING"
@Toc "NODE_TTYPES"
@{CODE}

	@{u}Tooltype BOOTLOGO@{uu}

		Setting this to 'NO' will cause the CyberGraphX Bootlogo not to be
	shown at boot time for this card.


@EndNode


@Node "NODE_TTYPES_DRAGGING" "CyberGraphX4.guide/NODE_TTYPES_DRAGGING"
@Prev "NODE_TTYPES_BOOTLOGO"
@Next "NODE_TTYPES_MULTIMEDIAMEM"
@Toc "NODE_TTYPES"
@{CODE}

	@{u}Tooltype DRAGGING@{uu}

		This makes it is possible to keep multiple screens in video memory
	allowing for very fast screen swaps. The trade off is that you will loose screen
	dragging. Do you wish to have dragable screens like normal amiga screens do ?
	Defaults to 'YES'. Not supported by all cards, though (e.g. CVisionPPC)

@EndNode



@Node "NODE_TTYPES_MULTIMEDIAMEM" "CyberGraphX4.guide/NODE_TTYPES_MULTIMEDIAMEM"
@Prev "NODE_TTYPES_DRAGGING"
@Next "NODE_TTYPES_PACKED24"
@Toc "NODE_TTYPES"
@{CODE}

	@{u}Tooltype MULTIMEDIAMEM (CV3D only)@{uu}

		If MULTIMEDIAMEM=YES CGX will reserve 1MB on the CV64/3D for 3D
	Textures & Video Overlay options. If 'NO', CV64/3D will then act like a card
	that does not have these options, like PicassoII. You will get the full 4MB
	for screens with a Z3 machine (Z2 gets 3.5MB). MULTIMEDIAMEM defaults to YES
	(where 3MB can be used for screens).

@EndNode



@Node "NODE_TTYPES_PACKED24" "CyberGraphX4.guide/NODE_TTYPES_PACKED24"
@Prev "NODE_TTYPES_MULTIMEDIAMEM"
@Next "NODE_TTYPES_PASSTHROUGH"
@Toc "NODE_TTYPES"
@{CODE}

	@{u}Tooltype PACKED24 (CVPPC/BVPPC only)@{uu}

	 	By setting tooltype PACKED24 to 'YES' packed pixel mode for 24bit
	resolutions is enabled. This allows higher refresh rates and requires less memory. 
	As a drawback, some accelerated graphics operations and cpu rendering
	slows down.

@EndNode



@Node "NODE_TTYPES_PASSTHROUGH" "CyberGraphX4.guide/NODE_TTYPES_PASSTHROUGH"
@Prev "NODE_TTYPES_PACKED24"
@Next "NODE_TTYPES_SCROLLMASK"
@Toc "NODE_TTYPES"
@{CODE}

	@{u}Tooltype PASSTHROUGH@{uu}

		If this option is disabled (='NO'), the monitor switch on the selected
	CyberGraphX card is deactivated. This option is required for multi
	monitor systems."

@EndNode


@Node "NODE_TTYPES_SCROLLMASK" "CyberGraphX4.guide/NODE_TTYPES_SCROLLMASK"
@Prev "NODE_TTYPES_PASSTHROUGH"
@Next "NODE_TTYPES_USEROXXLER"
@Toc "NODE_TTYPES"
@{CODE}

	@{u}Tooltype SCROLLMASK@{uu}

		Enables masking when scrolling/moving rectangles with a mask in
	256 colour modes. Setting this to 'NO' will speed up scrolling of text
	in a shell but might cause text crsr refresh problems with programs such
	as CED V2/V3 (not V4).


@EndNode


@Node "NODE_TTYPES_USEROXXLER" "CyberGraphX4.guide/NODE_TTYPES_USEROXXLER"
@Prev "NODE_TTYPES_SCROLLMASK"
@Next "NODE_TOOLS"
@Toc "NODE_TTYPES"
@{CODE}

	@{u}Tooltype USEROXXLER (CV64 only)@{uu}

		With the default of 'USEROXXLER=YES' the driver uses the special
	planar2chunky hardware on the CV64 to convert planar to chunky, _both_
	for fast memory and video memory destinations.

@EndNode



