@Toc "NODE_CGXMODE_MONWND"
@{CODE}

	@{u}Bandwidth [MHz]@{uu}

		This is the maximum dots per second that your monitor can do.
	This is sometimes called dot clock or driving clock frequency. This is measured
	in Megahertz (MHz). This is the number of signal periods per seconds. 1 time per
	second = 1 Hz. 1kHz = 1000Hz (One thousand Hz), 1MHz=1000000Hz (One million Hz).
	If you set the bandwidth to high then the display may become fuzzy or blurry.

@EndNode

@Node "NODE_CGXMODE_MONWND_HFREQMIN" "CyberGraphX4.guide/NODE_CGXMODE_MONWND_HFREQMIN"
@Prev "NODE_CGXMODE_MONWND_BANDWIDTH"
@Next "NODE_CGXMODE_MONWND_HFREQMAX"
@Toc "NODE_CGXMODE_MONWND"
@{CODE}

	@{u}Minimum Horizontal Frequency [kHz]@{uu}

		This is the minimum number of times that your monitor can write a
        horizontal scan line (left to right) in a second. This is one of the
        number you must enter correctly and should not guess! Underdriving your
        monitor could damage it. Older and 'cheaper' monitors do not have any
        protection against this. Some newer and 'better' monitors have
        protection against underdriving.. but you should never count on that. It
        is best to use the correct number for your monitor! This number is
        measured in Kilohertz (kHz).

@EndNode

@Node "NODE_CGXMODE_MONWND_HFREQMAX" "CyberGraphX4.guide/NODE_CGXMODE_MONWND_HFREQMAX"
