@{CODE}

	@{u}Maximum Horizontal Frequency [kHz}@{uu}

		This is the maximum number of times that your monitor can write a
        horizontal scan line (left to right) in a second. Overdriving your
        monitor could damage it. Older and 'cheaper' monitors do not have any
        protection against this. Some newer and 'better' monitors have
        protection against overdriving.. but you should never count on that. It
        is best to use the correct number for your monitor! This number is
        measured in Kilohertz (kHz).

@EndNode

@Node "NODE_CGXMODE_MONWND_HSYNCMINTIME" "CyberGraphX4.guide/NODE_CGXMODE_MONWND_HSYNCMINTIME"
@Prev "NODE_CGXMODE_MONWND_HFREQMAX"
@Next "NODE_CGXMODE_MONWND_HSYNCMINPULSE"
@Toc "NODE_CGXMODE_MONWND"
@{CODE}

        @{u}Minimum Time Horizontal Synchronization [탎]@{uu}

		This is the minimum time for the horizintal Blanking Period
        (Sync Length) that the monitor can handle. The horizontal Blanking
        period (Sync Length) is how long it takes the monitor to move the beam
        from the end of one scan line to the next and start 'drawing' again on
        the next scan line. Some monitors have a minimum limit on how short this
        time may be. The number is in Microseconds (not Dot(s)). If your
        monitor's manual only has numbers for Dot(s) for Vertical
        Synchronization use this formula to convert it:

        탎 = ( 1 / (Vertical Resolution in seconds + blanking period)) * Line(s) * 1000000

@EndNode

@Node "NODE_CGXMODE_MONWND_HSYNCMINPULSE" "CyberGraphX4.guide/NODE_CGXMODE_MONWND_HSYNCMINPULSE"
@Prev "NODE_CGXMODE_MONWND_HSYNCMINTIME"
@Next "NODE_CGXMODE_MONWND_VFREQMIN"
@Toc "NODE_CGXMODE_MONWND"
@{CODE}

	@{u}Minimum Pulse time Horizontal Synchronization [탎]@{uu}

        	This is the minimum time for the Pulse Length (Sync Period).
        This is the minimum time window that the monitor can be triggered to
        move the beam to the next line. If its too small the monitor can't
        detect the Pulse to move the beam to the next scan line. If your
        monitor's manual only has numbers for Line(s) for Vertical
        Synchronization use this formula to convert it:

        탎 = ( 1 / (Vertical Resolution in seconds + blanking period)) * Line(s) * 1000000

@EndNode

